‚Äâ Small dogs may be tiny in size, but when it comes to grooming, they often come with big needs‚Äîespecially elegant breeds like the Cavalier King Charles Spaniel. Whether you're a proud Cavvy parent or caring for another small dog breed like Shih Tzus, Yorkies, or Pomeranians, this guide has you covered.

Why Grooming Is So Important for Small Dogs

Small breeds often live indoors and are close to their humans (and furniture) at all times. This means they need to be clean, brushed, and healthy not only for their own well-being, but also to keep your home fresh and tidy. Regular grooming helps:
  • Prevent painful matting and tangles
  • Reduce shedding
  • Spot potential skin issues early
  • Maintain good hygiene around eyes, ears, paws, and rear
  • Keep your dog comfortable and adorable!

Cavalier King Charles Spaniel Grooming Routine

These royal pups have a moderately long, silky coat with feathering on their ears, legs, chest, and tail. Here's how to keep your Cavalier looking regal:

üíá Brushing

  • Tool: Use a high-quality slicker brush or a dual comb.
  • Recommended: 2-in-1 slicker brush and detangling comb set ‚Äì helps reduce tangles and prevent matting.

‚úÇÔ∏è Trimming

  • Cavaliers don't need full haircuts, but regular touch-up trims are key.
  • Focus Areas: Paws, sanitary area, ears, and feathering.
  • Pro Tool: Grooming scissors kit with safety tips ‚Äì ideal for home trimming without risk of injury.

üëÇ Ear Cleaning

  • Cavaliers' floppy ears can trap moisture and cause infections.
  • Wipe ears weekly using cotton pads and a pet-safe ear solution or these ear wipes.

üëÅÔ∏è Eye Care

  • Use a damp cloth or pet eye wipes daily to prevent tear stains, especially on light-coated Cavaliers.

üêæ Nail Clipping

  • How often: Every 3‚Äì4 weeks
  • Hear clicking? That's your cue.
  • Try this: Pet nail trimmer and grinder set ‚Äì quiet, safe, and easy for small dogs.

Grooming Tips for Other Small Breeds

If you have another little pup, here are some quick notes:
  • Shih Tzus & Maltese: Daily brushing and frequent trims due to fast-growing hair.
  • Yorkies: Silky coats require detangling spray and consistent brushing.
  • Pomeranians: Weekly deshedding is a must to prevent matting.
  • Miniature Poodles: Regular grooming every 4‚Äì6 weeks is non-negotiable.

‚Äâ L'Or√©al's Color Wow Acquisition: A Bold Move in the Premium Haircare Race L'Or√©al's June 2025 acquisition of Color Wow marks a pivotal moment in the beauty industry's push toward premiumization and consolidation. By securing a brand synonymous with salon-quality haircare, L'Or√©al aims to fortify its position in a high-margin segment primed for growth. Why the Premium Haircare Market Matters The global haircare market is projected to exceed $60 billion by 2028, with premium products capturing the fastest growth. Consumers, particularly millennials and Gen Z, are increasingly willing to pay a premium for science-backed, efficacy-driven products that deliver visible results. Color Wow's reputation as a ‚Äústylist's favorite‚Äù aligns perfectly with this trend, offering L'Or√©al access to a loyal customer base and a portfolio of award-winning formulas like its Root Cover Up Powder and Dream Coat spray. Strategic Rationale: A Triple Win for L'Or√©al Premium Segment Dominance: Color Wow's $300 million revenue (doubling in three years) and 40‚Äì60% profit margins highlight the profitability of premium haircare. L'Or√©al's Professional Products Division, which generated ‚Ç¨4.89 billion in 2024, now gains a foothold in styling and color correction‚Äîcategories with double-digit growth rates.Omnichannel Synergy: Color Wow's hybrid distribution model (salons, Sephora, Amazon) complements L'Or√©al's global retail network. By expanding Color Wow's presence in Asia and Europe, L'Or√©al can capitalize on untapped markets where premium haircare demand is soaring.R&D & Innovation Boost: L'Or√©al's $1.5 billion annual R&D investment can accelerate Color Wow's pipeline, while cost efficiencies from shared supply chains could improve margins further. Valuation: Paying a Premium for Growth While the exact purchase price remains undisclosed, industry sources suggest a valuation near $1 billion, implying a 25‚Äì30x EV/EBITDA multiple (Color Wow's EBITDA is estimated at $33‚Äì40 million). This aligns with L'Or√©al's own 18.9x EV/EBITDA multiple, which is elevated compared to the broader CPG sector but justified by its scale and innovation. Risks and Competing Forces - Niche Brand Threats: Smaller players like IGK Hair or Ouai, which emphasize affordability and social media-savvy branding, could erode L'Or√©al's premium positioning unless it maintains its innovation edge. - Sustainability Pressure: Rising demand for eco-friendly products (e.g., Unilever's Wild brand) forces L'Or√©al to balance premium pricing with green initiatives. - Market Saturation: Over-indexing on premium haircare could backfire if demand softens in mature markets like North America, where tariffs already pressured sales in 2024. ‚Äâ Levi Strauss LEVI has a simple strategy to deal with U.S. tariffs: stop offering less-popular styles during the holiday shopping season so they can avoid having to offer discounts to move inventory. The leading maker of jeans and other denim clothes on Thursday lifted its annual profit and revenue forecast, projecting strong demand for new styles and collections including dresses, skirts and wide-legged jeans even as shoppers are economizing due to the climbing prices of most goods. "We are taking a hard look at productivity in our assortments," Levi Strauss' Chief Financial Officer Harmit Singh told Reuters, cutting styles and colors that are not selling, and making way for new product. "And so, we're reducing our markdowns." Other companies including toymaker Hasbro HAS are also cutting less-popular lines. That approach has been used before in difficult times such as the pandemic, by Nike NKE for instance. Levi Strauss is focusing on a "common assortment" of products, meaning it is producing similar or identical merchandise in various markets, Singh said. This gives Levi Strauss the "flexibility and the agility to move product around the world," he said. U.S. President Donald Trump's tariffs on countries including China, Cambodia, Vietnam and Bangladesh have forced companies to rethink supply chains and import strategies as goods are often subject to layered tariffs. It could cost tens of thousands of dollars more to clear a shipping container of jeans at customs. This will boost retail prices for shoppers, especially during the crucial holiday shopping period. Levi's operating margin for the latest quarter rose 7.5% from 1.5% a year earlier. Analysts cheered the company's decision to tightly control stock-keeping units, or SKUs, an industry term for inventory. "Levi's move to reduce non-productive SKUs is a smart and sustainable strategy," said Angeli Gianchandani, adjunct instructor at New York University's School of Professional Studies. "Nike pursued a similar strategy through its "fewer, bigger, bolder" approach, which helped simplify assortments ... Brands like Coach and Uniqlo have also benefited from editing down to focus on hero products." Hasbro said in April that the toymaker was doing a "significant amount of SKU reduction" and importing fewer items from China as a defense against tariffs. Hasbro CEO Christian Cocks said: "We are changing what the SKU mix looks like inside of the aisles for the U.S. so that we can favor India-based SKUs, which maybe are older SKUs but are tried and true." Smaller vendors who sell on Amazon AMZN are cutting SKUs to offset the impact of paying tariffs and commission fees, and offering sales on discounting events like Black Friday and Cyber Monday, analysts said. E-commerce marketing consultancy Front Row, which works with beauty and haircare brands including Unilever's Tatcha and Procter & Gamble's Ouai, said some of its clients reduced the number of products offered for Amazon's 98-hour Prime Day. U.S. retailers drove $7.9 billion during July 8, making the first 24 hours of Prime Day the highest ecommerce shopping day so far this year, according to Adobe Analytics. ‚ÄúA lot of our brands are considering less SKUs,‚Äù Front Row Senior Vice President of Commercial Operations Alexandra Carmody said. "They're trying to figure out how to optimize the 20% of their assortments that make up 80% of their sales." Bogg Bag, which sells $80 plastic totes at Dick's Sporting Goods and on Amazon, is rolling back the number of items that will be on physical and virtual shelves this U.S. holiday shopping season to focus on the best-selling items, Chief Executive Kim Vaccarella said.
